CHINWENDU NNADOZIE; INNOCENT OWEH MINNA / ABUJA – The National Examinations Council (NECO) has released the 2020 Senior School Certificate Examinations (SSCE) internal results and announced a new date for candidates who could not sit for the June/July 2020 examinations due to the nationwide #EndSARS protest. Registrar/Chief Executive of NECO, Professor Godswill Obioma, disclosed this at NECO headquarters in Minna on Wednesday. Prof. Obioma noted that out of the 1, 209, 992 candidates that sat for the examination, 894,101 made five credits and above, including English and Mathematics. ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! A total of 1, 221, 447 candidates registered for the June/ July 2020 SSCE examination (internal) – 665, 830 males and 555,617 females – out of which 33, 470, cutting across both genders, were involved in different forms of examination malpractices. He explained that candidates’ performances in 2020 was more impressive compared to year 2019. “Candidates who made five credits and above, including English Language and Mathematics, are 894,101, representing 73.89% when compared to 2019 June/July SSCE figures of 829,787, with an increase of 2.3%,” he said. Mass Closure Of Nigerian Varsities, Disastrous, Counterproductive –Afe Babalola States Receive N123.348bn Performance Grant From FG Candidates who made five credits and above, irrespective of English Language and Mathematics, is 1,112,041, representing 91.91%. When compared to 2019 June/July SSCE figure of 1,042,989, there is an increase of 2.01%. The registrar attributed the achievements of NECO in conducting globally accepted examinations to the evolution of strategies to check examination frauds. He said: “The number of candidates involved in various forms of malpractice in 2020 is 33, 470, representing 2.61%, whereas 40, 630, representing 3.53% cases, was recorded in 2019.” He said NECO would continue to maintain zero-tolerance for examination cheats and announced the recommendation for the de-recognition of 12 centres for two years for their involvement in cheating: 1 in the FCT, 4 in Adamawa, 2 in Kaduna, 2 in Katsina, 2 in Niger, and 1 in Taraba State. He exonerated NECO staff of involvement in the Fabian Kings and Queens International School, Kaduna saga. “We discovered that it was an internally arranged mercenary that was dictating answers. No infractions from NECO staff. “However, we have blacklisted the school, supervisors, and invigilators,” he said. Meanwhile, NECO has assured the 233,000 candidates who missed the June/July SSCE examinations as a result of the #EndSARS protest that they would be given the opportunity to write their papers from Monday, February 1, 2021, to Wednesday, March 3, 2021. Obioma named the states affected by the protest as Abia, Enugu, Edo, River, Ondo, Ekiti, Osun, and Lagos. The others are Oyo, Kano, Ogun, and the FCT. He said the affected subjects were Chemistry (Practical), Economics, Technological Drawing, Food and Nutrition, and Further Mathematics. According to him, the results of the affected candidates would be pending until supplementary exams were conducted for the papers missed. “These special arrangements will be at no extra cost to these candidates. “Upon release of the 2020 SSCE internal results, those of the affected candidates will be pending for those papers missed and would be subsequently updated after the supplementary examination results are released”, he said.